│ 458   //      class need checking against each other.                                   │
│ 459                                                                                     │
│ 460   // We use the following (greedy) algorithm to construct the groups                │
│ 461   // For every pointer in the equivalence class:                                    │
│ 462   //   For each existing group:                                                     │
│ 463   //   - if the difference between this pointer and the min/max bounds              │
│ 464   //     of the group is a constant, then make the pointer part of the              │
│ 465   //     group and update the min/max bounds of that group as required.             │
│ 466                                                                                     │
│ 467   CheckingGroups.clear();                                                           │
│ 468                                                                                     │
│ 469   // If we need to check two pointers to the same underlying object                 │
│ 470   // with a non-constant difference, we shouldn't perform any pointer               │
│ 471   // grouping with those pointers. This is because we can easily get                │
│ 472   // into cases where the resulting check would return false, even when             │
│ 473   // the accesses are safe.                                                         │
│ 474   //                                                                                │
│ 475   // The following example shows this:                                              │
│ 476   // for (i = 0; i < 1000; ++i)                                                     │
│ 477   //   a[5000 + i * m] = a[i] + a[i + 9000]                                         │
│ 478   //                                                                                │
│ 479   // Here grouping gives a check of (5000, 5000 + 1000 * m) against                 │
│ 480   // (0, 10000) which is always false. However, if m is 1, there is no              │
│ 481   // dependence. Not grouping the checks for a[i] and a[i + 9000] allows            │
